messages.content: You are tasked with creating a structured output from the provided user message.

Full request path:
- /consumer/{consumerID}/printingschemas/{printingSchemaID}

Allowed methods (based on the source code):
- all HTTP methods (wildcard): false
- HEAD: false
- POST: false
- OPTIONS: false
- TRACE: false
- GET: false
- PUT: true
- DELETE: true
- PATCH: false

Explanation:
- The file contains two explicit @RequestMapping annotations that use the exact path "/consumer/{consumerID}/printingschemas/{printingSchemaID}":
  - @RequestMapping(value = "/consumer/{consumerID}/printingschemas/{printingSchemaID}", method = RequestMethod.DELETE) — deleteConsumerPrintingSchema(...)
  - @RequestMapping(value = "/consumer/{consumerID}/printingschemas/{printingSchemaID}", method = RequestMethod.PUT) — editConsumerPrintingSchema(...)
  These two annotations make DELETE and PUT explicitly accepted for that path.
- GET and POST in this controller are mapped to "/consumer/{consumerID}/printingschemas" (no printingSchemaID), so they do not apply to the path with {printingSchemaID}.
- There is no class-level @RequestMapping that would change the prefix for these methods.
- No mapping in the code explicitly allows HEAD, OPTIONS, TRACE, PATCH, or a wildcard (all methods). Per your instruction, I base the answer only on explicit mappings in the code (not on framework defaults like implicit HEAD/OPTIONS handling), so those methods are marked false.
